target_title: Add support for adding Matrix IM details to a contact

note.body: From the Matrix point of view, you have an identifier (commonly referred to as mxid) that looks like `@rupert:gnome.org`, which is is what should be stored in the contact details. Then, there’s a [Matrix URI scheme](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.12/appendices/#matrix-uri-scheme) and Fractal knows how to open such a URI. So Contacts would need to open `matrix:u/rupert:gnome.org?action=chat`, which addresses Niels’ third point.

Allow easily copying phone numbers and opening the Calls application with them

note.body: I assume evolution is using an URI? Calls exposes actions on DBus that contacts could use but there's no portal atm.

Personally, I think that:

* It should just silently import all the base64 encoded embedded `PHOTO` field data (which is what Evolution / Contacts would export anyway, so that already facilitates transfers across computers)

* There should be a preference toggle switch that allows fetching contacts' remote avatars (from Gravatar, Google, etc.) when not already present as an embedded base64 photo (which should override the remote version anyway) and keeping them in sync, vs "Only on initial import of each contact", vs "Not at all". I think this would be better than prompting the user on each import. I suspect that a vast majority of people will prefer to fetch remote contact avatars (when no local version is available) rather than having nothing at all.

target_title: Allow easily copying phone numbers and opening the Calls application with them

note.body:
Reworded the description a bit for clarity. Probably related: [GNOME Calls' "contacts-integration" tag](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/calls/-/issues/?label_name[]=contacts-integration).

---

Indeed it would be nice to have a copy button (for touchscreen devices) next to each number, and a call button next to each number to launch the corresponding application (such as GNOME Calls) with the number.

I see that in Evolution's contacts GUI, if a call handling application is installed, Evolution hyperlinks numbers and it opens Skype (!) or [GNOME Calls]() with them.

Someone should probably look at how Evolution does it in their code as inspiration for an implementation in GNOME Contacts. Is there a special portal way to do this in GNOME that @guidog / @devrtz / @antonok are aware of and could recommend, or is Evolution's approach the state of the art?

Presumably it would be a newcomers-friendly task that we could tag?

---

P.s.: IMHO, as numbers can be a mess (ex: missing or incorrect international/regional prefixes), I think the receiving app (ex: GNOME Calls) should just pre-populate the number in an editable dialpad's field that the user can confirm before calling? I'm not sure if that's already the case.

note.body:
I think it's unclear, because a lot of our groupware is ultimately a front-end for evolution-data-server, but we have no obvious "default" settings front-end for EDS as a whole (other than Evolution, which is much more than that).

Maybe it's time to develop a small UI library for this, like gnome-bluetooth, constrained to the few uses we know our core apps share? This case is an example where Calendar and Contacts both seem like the reasonable place to have the setting, but then there's the obvious code duplication. There are some similar bits in GNOME Online Accounts and GNOME Settings, as well.

Photos do not sync with iCloud via CardDAV

note.body:
Not sure what code is shared between Evolution Contacts and Gnome Contacts, but the behaviour was the same.

I re-tested and, in the meantime, Apple has changed the way photos are associated with contacts. They no longer use links but instead embed the photo in the contact:
```
PHOTO;TYPE=jpeg;ENCODING=b:...
```

Embedded photos are shown correctly in Evolution and Gnome Contacts.

Affected users need to make an update to the affected contacts on their phone or somewhere else in iWorld to get the photo embedded. It seems, you have to update the contact photo (with the same photo) to have the photo included in the contact (instead of linked).

I suggest to close this issue.

note.body:
Actually, I realize now that the searchentry widget is not a searchbar "mode" that can be toggled on and off, it just is shown there permanently. Therefore, the only way to de-filter is to clear the searchentry.

As such, if the current design is to be retained, then the `Esc` key should be mapped to the clear action on the search entry, when the searchentry is focused and no multiple-contacts selection is active. It would be like clicking the clear action icon in the searchentry, but without needing to use the mouse.
